<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?><entry xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:planet="http://planet.intertwingly.net/"><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-3455785628713238703.post-4070678212072125371</id><link href="http://kdphd.blogspot.com/feeds/4070678212072125371/comments/default" rel="replies" type="application/atom+xml"/><link href="http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=3455785628713238703&amp;postID=4070678212072125371" rel="replies" type="text/html"/><link href="http://www.blogger.com/feeds/3455785628713238703/posts/default/4070678212072125371" rel="edit" type="application/atom+xml"/><link href="http://www.blogger.com/feeds/3455785628713238703/posts/default/4070678212072125371" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml"/><link href="http://kdphd.blogspot.com/2010/07/top-three-pieces-of-advice.html" rel="alternate" type="text/html"/><title>Top Three Pieces of Advice</title><content type="xhtml"><div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">I've gone to a bunch of women in computer science focused events over the past few years.  Of the many pieces of advice shared, these are the three that have really stuck in my head.  They're paraphrased, but hopefully correctly attributed.<br/><ol><br/><li>While men can get away with not having a Ph.D. and still be respected in the field (see Gates, Bill), women can't yet.  Get one.  Then do whatever you want.  - Mary Lou Jepsen at Grace Hopper<br/></li><li>The reviewer of your paper is always right.  If they completely misunderstood the paper, you now know you need to rewrite it.  - CRA-W Grad Cohort &quot;How to Write a Paper&quot; session<br/></li><li>Spend money to make your life easier - Women in Theory &quot;Work/Life Balance&quot; panel.  Also heard at a Grace Hopper panel in the form:  If your mother-in-law is coming to visit the same weekend as a paper deadline, pay someone to clean your house.<br/></li></ol><br/>Have other advice?  Do share.</div><div class="commentbar"><p/><span class="commentbutton" href="http://kdphd.blogspot.com/feeds/4070678212072125371/comments/default"/><a href="http://kdphd.blogspot.com/feeds/4070678212072125371/comments/default"><img class="commenticon" src="/images/feed-icon.png"/> Subscribe to comments</a><![CDATA[  | ]]><a href="http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=3455785628713238703&amp;postID=4070678212072125371"><img class="commenticon" src="/images/post-icon.png"/> Post a comment</a></div></content><updated planet:format="July 01, 2010 05:48 PM">2010-07-01T17:48:00Z</updated><published planet:format="July 01, 2010 05:48 PM">2010-07-01T17:48:00Z</published><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="advice"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="women in cs"/><author><name>Sorelle Friedler</name><email>noreply@blogger.com</email><uri>https://plus.google.com/100604236318346733938</uri></author><source><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-3455785628713238703</id><category term="conferences"/><category term="cs"/><category term="education"/><category term="election '08"/><category term="women in cs"/><category term="politics"/><category term="teaching"/><category term="women in science"/><category term="grad student life"/><category term="socg"/><category term="gay issues"/><category term="theory"/><category term="women in theory"/><category term="ghana"/><category term="maps"/><category term="research"/><category term="sexism"/><category term="computational geometry"/><category term="current reading"/><category term="job search"/><category term="racism"/><category term="soda"/><category term="Obama"/><category term="teachers"/><category term="the environment"/><category term="Swarthmore"/><category term="algorithms"/><category term="classism"/><category term="dc"/><category term="dc vote"/><category term="google"/><category term="grace hopper"/><category term="me"/><category term="reviewing"/><category term="title ix"/><category term="women in academia"/><category term="TA-ing"/><category term="academia"/><category ter